04560nam a22007575i 9780231527880DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012021330  a97802315278807 a10.7312/mont157322doi  a(DE-B1597)459147  a(OCoLC)979573750  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aTX645b.M6613 2012 4aTX645 .M6613 2012 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a641.3009a641.51 aMontanari, Massimo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLet the Meatballs Rest :bAnd Other Stories About Food and Culture /cMassimo Montanari. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArts and Traditions of the Table: Perspectives on Culinary History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Things and Ideas -- t2. The Status of Foods -- t3. Adventures in Cooking -- t4. The Gastronomy of Hunger -- t5. Flavors -- t6. Pleasure and Health -- t7. The Beautiful and the Good -- t8. Convivial Rituals -- t9. Table Practices and Manners -- t10. “Identity” Declined in the Plural -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKnown for his entertaining investigations into culinary practice, Massimo Montanari turns his hungry eye to the phenomenon of food culture, food lore, cooking methods, and eating habits throughout history. An irresistible buffet of one hundred concise and engaging essays, this collection provides stimulating food for thought for those curious about one of life's most fundamental pleasures.Focusing on the selection, preparation, and mythology of food, Montanari traverses such subjects as the status of the pantry over the centuries, the various strategies of cooking over time, the gastronomy of famine, the science of flavors, the changing characteristics of convivial rituals, the customs of the table, and the ever-evolving identity of food. He shows that cooking not only is a decisive part of our cultural heritage but also communicates essential information about our material and intellectual well-being. From the invention of basic bread making to chocolate's reputation for decadence, Montanari positions food culture as a lens through which we can plot changes in historical values and social and economic trends. Even the biblical tale of Jacob buying Esau's birthright for a bowl of lentils is a text full of essential meaning, representing civilization's important shift from a hunting to an agrarian society. Readers of all backgrounds will enjoy these delectable insights and their easy consumption in one companionable volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCookingxHistory. 0aCookingxPhilosophy. 0aFood habitsxHistory. 0aFood habitsxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aBrombert, Beth Archer.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mont1573240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231527880423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231527880.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK